5: And here it is! Sorry for the wait.
9:
This is your vaunted cooking, is it?
It is certainly rich in color...
17:
I picked up this recipe from a village
in the desert. It's got a bit of a kick to
it, doesn't it?
19:
A kick? Yes, I suppose the flavor is
quite bold.
22:
It's 'cause of all the spices. They give
it that strong aroma—and start a
fire in your mouth!
27:
I see that Schult is getting more
used to speaking with humans now.
30:
When we first met him, he spoke
even less! It seemed that until I
came along, he hadn't even uttered
a single word in hundreds of years.
33:
Indeed, I was a... What is the word
you humans use in such situations?
45:
(A NEET dragon... There's a joke
somewhere in here that I'm too
scared to make...)
48:
This food is very good indeed.
Delicious? Delectable?
50: It pleases me—I shall have more!
55:
Is his stomach a black hole or
something?! How much do dragons
eat?!
59:
What seems to be the problem? Are
you in pain, human?
64: N-no, I'm fine! It's nothing, really.
69:
I see. You eat too much, Schult. Alk is
concerned that he cannot afford
the cost of food.
74:
It's okay! Schult definitely DOES eat a
lot, but I'll manage somehow. He
seems to really enjoy the food, after
all.
79:
Ah, yes... it's coming back to me
now.
Humans assign value to
commodities and exchange them in
an "economy".
81:
Very well. I will earn my keep and
seek a means to acquire currency.
91:
This is an express delivery—please
hurry!
94:
Of course! Greatwyrm Delivery
Services is on the job!
98:
All right, this is bound for the plaza in
the city to the west. I've already
notified them, so they'll be... ready
for you.
101:
The plaza to the west. Understood.
Leave it to me.
106:
A service where a dragon delivers
your stuff wherever you want... That's
not a bad idea. Did you come up
with this?
110:
Yep. Schult is perfectly suited for
doing deliveries! This business
opportunity was staring us right in
the face.
113:
At this rate, he'll be making more
than enough money to offset his
massive appetite!
116:
Don't count your chickens before
they hatch...
122:
Damage report: 20 people injured
due to falls. 8 roofs blown away. 15
livestock unaccounted for.
126:
That's what happens when you try
to use an Ancient's power to start a
business.
130:
Apologies. I had intended to fly to
my destination without causing a
disturbance.
135:
Don't worry, it's not your fault, Schult.
I should have considered the
possibility something like this could
happen.
138:
But this will make it difficult to earn
more money.
143:
Forget earnin' money, you're about
to be in a whole lot of debt.
146:
Mister Alk, Lord Schult... Please take
this. I know it's not much, but it's the
least we can do.
148:
The girls and I found employment in
Palpebra working as waitresses.
Please use this for your food
expenses.
151:
You went through all that trouble? I
mean, I really appreciate it, but you
shouldn't have...
154:
They're friends of his, I don't see a
problem with takin' the money!
159:
Th-this is a lot! Even after I buy
everything I need to make Schult's
food, I'll still have some left over!
163:
Lucia, Aileen, Mertina... I am in your
debt. Thank you.
166:
Lord Schult... It is an honor to be of
service to you!
172:
I would have liked to work and earn
a living for myself.
179:
By the way, Schult, I had something
to talk to you about.
182:
I haven't told anyone else yet, but
from what I recall, ancient dragons
don't need to consume food to
survive... Am I mistaken?
186: It appears my secret is out...
189:
I... wished to be like you humans. To
blend in with you, I felt it necessary
to emulate your behavior. To eat. To
work.
193:
All of that commotion for a reason
like that? I suppose I can
understand wanting to fit in. What
was it like? Being human.
196:
It was... interesting.
No, perhaps even fun.
I fear I've wronged Sir Alk, however.
200:
You don't need to worry about Alk. I
think he's enjoyed this experience, in
his own way.
203:
Yet the expression on his face
suggested otherwise.
207:
That's simply the type of person he
is—he enjoys enduring hardships to
help his friends. Similar to Lucia,
wouldn't you say?
211:
I see.
Humans are indeed fascinating
creatures...
214:
It's curious. Despite being an Ancient
that has lived for an eternity, you
have an almost child-like innocence
about you.
216:
I... apologize for my impertinence. I
should not say such things to a
great dragon.
220: I do not mind. 'Tis all the same to me.
223:
My ignorance is understandable—I
was a shut-in for so long, after all.
227:
Perhaps you should consider using
a different expression...
